 technology to the maximum extent possible; (c) focusing on the development of form factors based on well-defined standards to support lead platform integration; and
 (d) implementing a proactive, collaborative MGUE platform integration activity to mitigate risk and reduce cost for DoD force structure modernization.

 The MGUE program awarded three sole source contracts for the Inc 1 Technology Development Phase effort in September 2012, as follow-on efforts to the
 competitively awarded Modernized User Equipment (MUE) contracts awarded in June 2006. The effort spans the Technology Maturation and Risk Reduction Phase
 through design and includes integration and test of M-Code receivers into Service-nominated lead platforms. In first quarter FY2021, the program office converted the
 remaining Raytheon GRAM-S/M development effort to a Firm Fixed Price contract type at the direction of the Air Force Service Acquisition Executive. The contracts of
 the other two vendors remain primarily a Cost Plus Incentive Fee type contract. This effort also includes the security and compatibility certification of GPS receiver cards
 as a part of the integration effort. The lead platforms will select from the available vendors to integrate and perform operational testing with funding from the MGUE
 program. This supports compliance with PL 111-383, section 913.

 On 24 Oct 2024, the SAE signed an Acquisition Decision Memorandum to approve a switch from the Air Force's B-2 platform to the Army's Gray Eagle UAV as the
 MGUE Inc-1 lead aviation platform.

 The MGUE Inc 2 program developed an Acquisition Strategy to continue MGUE development by: addressing long term producibility of MGUE ASICs, identifying a U.S.
 owned trusted foundry for ASIC development, delivering GPS receiver cards to meet stringent Inc 2 requirements, and developing a modernized GPS handheld receiver
 to meet the needs of the Services. The MGUE Inc 2 program is being executed in four parts: 1) Risk Reduction Activities, 2) Miniature Serial Interface (MSI) Receiver
 Card Middle Tier Acquisition (MTA) rapid prototyping, followed by 3) Software Acquisition Pathway (SWP), and 4) Joint Modernized GPS HH Receiver Middle Tier
 Acquisition rapid prototyping effort. The Air Force SAE approved the MGUE Inc 2 Acquisition Strategy to include designation of two MTA Rapid Prototype efforts: 1) MSI
 Receiver Card (includes Next-Gen ASIC) and 2) Joint, Modernized Handheld Receiver. Furthermore, the SAE has approved the transition to a SWP following completion
 of MSI MTA to finish MSI development. MGUE Inc 2 awarded three full and open competitive contracts in Nov 2020 for MSI. Due to a bilaterally negotiated contract
 modification, one vendor's Period of Performance completed in November 2023. The government is currently planning the transition of the MSI development out of MTA
 Rapid Prototype acquisition pathway to the Software Pathway program first quarter FY 2026.

 The MGUE Inc 2 Aviation/Maritime program projected to execute in two parts: 1) risk reduction activities (FY2026) and 2) Aviation/Maritime Receiver Card Middle Tier
 Acquisition rapid prototyping effort (FY2027 and beyond). The SAE approved the transfer of the MGUE Inc 2 program from United States Space Force (USSF) to United
 States Air Force (USAF). MGUE Inc 2 Program Office is working closely with the Air Force counterpart on a transition plan.




