INSERT INTO public.pe_narratives (pe_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, accomplishments, planned_program, performance_metrics, other_program_funding, raw_text, content_hash, section_hashes, source_pdf, source_page, ingested_at) VALUES ($$1203010SF$$, 2026, $$Digital Engineering (DE) is one of four United States Space Force's (USSF) Focus areas in the Service's digital transformation and is a key enabler. The Space Force
was born as a digitally driven organization to meet the need to respond faster to global threats and to act as a force multiplier for the lean Service. The "USSF Vision
for a Digital Service," May 2021, signed by the Chief of Space Operations, states that "A key aim of [Digital Engineering] is to manage the complexity of contemporary
weapon system acquisition as well as accelerate and modernize the entire capability development lifecycle—from conception to deployment to operations and
sustainment.” The USSF Digital Engineering Ecosystem (DEE) stakeholders are from across the capability development lifecycle. Users include engineers, program
managers, force designers, requirements professionals, finance professionals, contracting professionals, logisticians, acquisition leaders and decision makers, mission
partners, industry connections, and all other participants in the Capability Development Lifecycle. The Department of Defense's (DoD) Defense Acquisition University
definition of DEE is, "The interconnected infrastructure, environment, and methodology (process, methods, and tools) used to store, access, analyze, and visualize
data and models to address the needs of stakeholders." The current funding profile will demonstrate a robust capability for approximately 2000 users with the goal
to scale up to accommodate users across the USSF. This includes cloud-hosted and on-premises virtual machines with integrated applications tailored to users for
access on users' desks through the web as well as demonstration of secure thin client and other user devices for user access. The modernized capability buildout is for
all security classification domains from Controlled
Information (CUI) to Secret, Top Secret (TS), Sensitive Compartmented Information (SCI) and Special
Access Program (SAP). For the SAP deployment, the program also provides initial capability for necessary secure lab space to conduct capability development using the
toolsets.

 Program Element 1203010SF, Space Force Information Technology (IT), Data Analytics, Digital Solutions, creates the foundation for the USSF's digital transformation,
 which will streamline acquisition, cybersecurity, life cycle management, and operations. This entails three distinct projects, unified in their goal to fully exploit modern
 information technology:

 Project 645620, Digital Engineering, develops a computing environment to support the digital engineering needs of program offices across Space Systems Command
 (SSC), the product of which would serve programs throughout their life cycles. It also develops and prototypes Artificial Intelligence (AI) capabilities to be utilized to meet
 emerging needs.
Advanced Component Development & Prototypes (ACD&P)
 Project 646017, Developmental Information Technology Infrastructure (DITI), delivers the tools, policies, and processes that program offices across SSC utilize to design
 their systems to meet cybersecurity requirements and then earn cyber certification.

 Project 646602, Integrated Operations Networking (ION), leverages existing network infrastructure, connecting it and enhancing its capability when needed, to meet the
 needs of critical kill webs.

 The FY 2026 request was reduced by $0.804M for Advisory and Assistance Services to promote efficiencies and advance the policies of the Administration in alignment
 with Executive Order 14222, "Implementing the President's Department of Government Efficiency Cost Efficiency Initiative".

 This program element may include necessary civilian pay expenses required to manage, execute, and deliver Space Force IT, Data Analytics, Digital Solutions
 capability. The use of such program funds would be in addition to the civilian pay expenses budgeted in program elements 1206392SF and 1206398SF.

 This effort is in Budget Activity 4, Advanced Component Development and Prototypes (ACD&P), because efforts are necessary to evaluate integrated technologies,
 representative modes or prototype systems in a high fidelity and realistic operating environment.$$, $$In FY 2026, all funds for Integrated Operations Networking (ION) are transferred from Project 646017 to 646602.

 The USSF's Integrated Operations Networking (ION) effort is a critical component of the Space Force's mission to enable the Battle Management, Command, Control,
 and Communications (BMC3) warfighter missions. ION will provide a secure, reliable, multi-classification data transport backbone across critical kill webs designed to
 defend against adversary operations. This ION communications backbone will provide high bandwidth with low latency for essential capabilities, connecting with the data
 platform, Unified Data Library, to ensure data exposure and dissemination occur using ION's resilient connectivity from sensors to C2 centers and tactical units. ION will
 integrate commercially available information technology (IT) capabilities to minimize government-unique tools, reducing technology debt and increasing agility against
 cyber threats.

 The ION program will prioritize the closure of priority kill-web gaps, as identified in the Space Force's Digital Services Ecosystem Strategic Requirements Document. The
 program will focus on developing a secure, reliable, and multi-classification transport layer to support space missions, with a emphasis on direct connection between all
 elements of force packages, establishing a special access program (SAP)-level network with overlays, and developing high-speed connectivity and high resilience to
 C2S. The ION program will also investigate opportunities to leverage existing efforts, such as MeshONE-T to support the development of ION.

 The ION program will be executed in accordance with the DoD's Cyber Strategy and the Space Force's cyber security policies and guidance. The program will
 implement Zero Trust (ZT) capabilities, cryptography modernization, and supply chain risk management (SCRM) to ensure the security and resilience of the ION
 network. The program will also explore the use of Artificial Intelligence (AI) applications to provide decision aids, automation, and computer decision support to make
 effective decisions in a complicated environment and reduce cognitive load.

 The increased funding in FY 2026 will enable the program to maintain a steady pace of execution throughout the year, ensuring that the Space Force can leverage the
 ION capability to enhance its mission effectiveness. The ION program will provide a critical capability to the Space Force, enabling the service to operate in a contested
 environment and to defend against adversary operations. The program will be executed in a manner that is consistent with the Space Force's priorities, including the
 development of a digital engineering ecosystem, the implementation of zero trust capabilities, and the modernization of cryptography and supply chain risk management.

