A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
Project 645620, Digital Engineering (DE), is delivering the Digital Engineering Ecosystem (DEE). DEE is a cloud-based, remotely accessible, Multi-Level-Security (MLS)
suite of applications, environments, and infrastructure that is easily scalable and provides the means to develop capabilities, store, access, architect, analyze, and
visualize data and models throughout the acquisition life cycle, from requirements planning, development, and production, through sustainment.

 DEE provides a unified enterprise environment for Space Systems Command (SSC) program offices, operations squadrons, other government stakeholders, and
 hardware and software vendors, enabling responsive, threat-informed product development, testing, deployment, training, mission planning, and on-orbit anomaly
 resolution. Key capabilities include: (1) Connecting multiple Digital Threads—a framework to link all the digital information about a space system, from initial design
 to operations, into a single, accessible system—integrating organizations such as members of the intel community, Space Warfighting Analysis Center (SWAC), and
 Space Operations Command (SpOC) to leverage threat models for smarter force design, requirements development, solution design, acquisition, and operations
 planning; (2) Connecting Classified Systems—facilitating seamless multi-domain engineering activities across multiple classification levels (e.g., CUI to TS, SCI, SAP);
 (3) Eliminating Redundant Systems—standardizing tools to enhance inte.g.ration and collaboration; (4) Achieving Cost Efficiencies— reducing costs through enterprise-
 level capabilities and economies of scale; (5) Enhancing Data-Driven Decisions—providing real-time accurate, relevant information for informed leadership decisions;
 and (6) Supporting Space Force's Digital Transformation—providing the applications and environment to advance the Chief of Space Operations' (CSO) vision of the
 Space Force as a "Digital Service," as outlined in the May 2021, U.S. Space Force Vision for a Digital Service.

 DEE supports DE by connecting acquisition, test, training, and operational data, models, and activities at the speed of relevance through the delivery of a hybrid cloud
 MLS modeling and data ecosystem. DEE establishes Authoritative Sources of Truth (ASOTs) and Single Sources of Truth (SSOTs) by incorporating data integration
 across multiple trusted sources. DEE is designed to connect engineers, program managers, force designers, requirements managers, logisticians, developmental and
 operational testers, training instructors and schoolhouses, operational commanders, senior decision makers, mission partners, industry and academia, and all other
 participants in the Capability Development Lifecycle.

 The DEE is designed to integrate information technology (IT), system security, software development, and data/network modernization to accelerate and modernize the
 USSF capability development lifecycle. It equips users with tools to enhance collaboration, user experience, and integration with mission partners and industry. DEE
 helps to assess technical risks posed by adversary threats by analyzing system and enterprise-level risks and incorporates agile software practices to scale platforms
 and infrastructure based on digital thread mission needs. The DEE provides deliberate data exposure and "normalizes” the data to make it meaningful and useful for any
 business or mission use cases.

 The DEE effort includes multiple DEE prototype solutions collectively known as the Digital Engineering Integrated Cloud-based Environment (DEICE) Tech Stack. These
 prototypes currently serve as the interim Digital Services Ecosystem (DSE) for USSF Capability Development as a cloud-based, remotely accessible, interconnected

