 Additionally, this project funds science, technology, and research study efforts supporting critical operational challenges and collaborating on fundamental advances
 in Artificial Intelligence (AI). These efforts include creating new algorithms, technologies, analysis tools, and solutions, and informs Department of Defense decision
 making on future force structures and capabilities. In one line of effort, this project funds a variety of graduate and post-graduate studies, projects and algorithms to
 operationalize AI by addressing senior leader sponsored, real-world challenges in Space Domain Awareness (SDA), Command & Control (C2), Advanced Space
 Training and other missions using the Department of the Air Force-Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) AI Accelerator. This line of effort has and will continue to
 transition AI algorithms and tools to USSF operational units. In another line of effort, this project improves how space forces are represented and modeled in Joint and
 other Services' wargaming and analysis to inform their force structure decisions and operational concepts.

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                     FY 2024     FY 2025      FY 2026
Title: Digital Engineering Integration                                                                                                     25.214      36.204       25.455
Description: USSF DEE integrates across multiple security environments and authoritative sources of truth. This effort integrates
space models over varying maturity levels to function within the DEE to enable test components the ability to evaluate high-fidelity
modeling & simulations of real-world space assets capabilities and limitations to inform Tactics, Techniques, and Procedures
(TTPs) that need to be developed by readiness components.

FY 2025 Plans:
Continue to incrementally build Digital Engineering and Integration prototype infrastructure to develop specific capability solutions
and assess their suitability for the long-term DEE solution. Do this by leveraging existing contract vehicles to award Other
Transaction Authority (OTA) agreements, Small Business Innovation Research (SBIR) Phase III contracts, and Information
Technology (IT) integration service contracts. Continue to prototype, develop, test, and establish a USSF DEE hosted on a hybrid
cloud platform for cloud-computing and database storage.

Develop and test a minimum viable product (MVP) DEE capability tailored to the needs of a small set of "early adopter” program
offices, containing prototype/demo digital engineering tools and collaboration workspaces. Work with those program offices'
system architects and systems engineers to refine the tools and environment to improve the user experience and grow the DEE
for broader use.

Establish and accredit new network connections to Special Access Program Platform-as-a-Service (PaaS) that will leverage
enterprise data availability and host digital tools and Model Based Systems Engineering (MBSE) tools in support of Kill Chain
analysis, digital acquisition source selection, rapid threat/intelligence integration, and budget support planning.



