A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
Project 646017, Space Systems Command (SSC) Developmental Information Technology Infrastructure (DITI) provides support to enterprise cybersecurity integration,
cyber capability development, and vulnerability management across SSC program offices. The project provides program offices support through their Authorizing Official
(AO) and Risk Management Framework (RMF) cyber assessment team, Zero Trust (ZT), cryptography program alignment, data and information availability, supply
chain risk management capabilities, and software management. Until FY 2026 when it transitions to a separate project, DITI also supported United States Space Force
(USSF) operational needs with the Integrated Operations Networking (ION) effort. The USSF's ION effort is a critical component of the Space Force's mission to enable
the Battle Management, Command, Control and Communications (BMC3) warfighter missions. ION will provide a secure, reliable, multi-classification data transport
backbone across critical kill webs designed to defend against adversary operations.

 DITI develops and implements cybersecurity tools and processes and alignment of cybersecurity policies and guidance though several efforts. The DITI project
 Directorate provides support to cybersecurity AOs and RMF cyber assessment teams for Authorization to Operate (ATO) decisions. DITI develops ZT strategies and
 architectures, executing a ZT pilot program to address legacy and future space systems that establish and mitigate threats against infrastructure. The Cryptography
 Modernization effort builds a central repository to track all crypto requirements to identify gaps, program risks, mitigation plans, and status tracking across SSC, per
 Department of the Air Force Manual (DAFMAN) 17-1302.

 This project's efforts focus on developmental cybersecurity and support generation and alignment of cybersecurity policy and guidance, cyber resiliency capability
 development, vulnerability management, data accessibility with automation, and program protection. DITI helps assess technical risks that operational users experience
 in SSC program offices or encounter by understanding the System and Enterprise-level risks posed by threats based on deployment and gathered feedback across
 SSC. Cybersecurity regulation and directives are synthesized, deconstructed, and applied to best determine implementation and standardization across various
 functions and mission sets. Capability development efforts include implementation of DoD cybersecurity policies and guidance such as DoD's Cyber Strategy, ZT
 Strategy, and capabilities. This includes efforts for enabling ZT capabilities in Space Systems and implementation of SSC ZT Guidance and Policy via pilot programs for
 both legacy and future ground and space systems in accordance with Executive Order 14028, "Improving the Nation's Cybersecurity,”, which requires federal agencies
 to establish plans to drive adoption of ZT Architecture. The projects pursued for ZT keeps pace with increasing cyber threats and modernizes existing infrastructure
 into SSC programs for mitigation against existing and future vulnerabilities. DITI Developmental Cybersecurity effort will deploy and enhance SSC Supply Chain Risk
 Management (SCRM) capabilities through development of SCRM AI/ML tools that will illuminate and monitor the space defense industrial base and provide real-time risk
 analysis to SSC Program Executive Offices (PEOs).




