 DITI's Program Protection effort develops databases, tools, and processes to organize information, reduce program-level redundancies, and clarify and update
 user guides, policy, and contract language to mitigate foreign threats and commercial risks to SSC programs. The effort also develops agile information access and
 authentication capabilities for the space operations environment to ensure information availability to combat against degradation and disruption.

 DITI produces and defines architectures for Data and AI. This provides context and governance for human machine teaming, and support for operations in the
 information environment, which is a key consideration in acquisition planning. DITI also contains the function of the SSC Command Data and AI Officer (CDAO). The
 CDAO explores pilots for the use of AI applications to provide decision aids, automation, and computer decision support to make effective decisions in a complicated
 environment and reduce cognitive load.

 DITI will test artificial intelligence (AI)/Human Machine Teaming pilots and approaches to augment Defensive Cyber Operators (DCO) capability and increase resilience
 of USSF systems against cyber threats. The Supply Chain Risk Management effort uses a commercial platform that brings public and private data sources with
 commercial artificial intelligence/machine learning (AI/ML) tools. This platform provides supply chain vendor vulnerabilities that could jeopardize mission capability.
 The Software and IT effort will deliver authorized cloud-based environments and expand digital mobility programs, providing more flexible, modernized, and capable IT
 mechanisms for the workforce to enable and propel mission success. A software management system will be created to foster superior software development and drive
 adoption of the industry standard Development-Security-Operations (DevSecOps) approach, accelerating program schedules and reducing security risk to space assets.

 The DITI Cryptography Modernization effort advocates for crypto requirements across SSC. The Crypto Modernization effort centralizes and streamlines crypto
 processes for SSC program offices through creating policy and guidance, strategy, and development to meet future program requirements and expand to meet
 cryptography requirements at an enterprise level. SSC program offices are required to provide cryptographic requirements to the Crypto Modernization Office per
 Department of the Air Force Manual (DAFMAN) 17-1302.

 The DITI Security Control Assessor (SCA) provides recommendation(s) to the Approving Official on residual risk rating and authorization decisions in line with National
 Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) compliance and Department of Defense Instruction (DoDI) 8510.01 (RMF).

 DITI is the authoritative source for enterprise tools and applications (ETAs), with effective and centrally managed licensing systems, a streamlined procurement process,
 fully migrated and accredited cloud-based environments. DITI provides strategic guidance on software matters, policies to foster superior software development, and
 drive adoption for Agile and Development-Security-Operations (DevSecOps) methodologies to revolutionize acquisition practices. A robust network infrastructure,
 tailored for the USSF, will demonstrate fast and reliable communication, support enterprise AI capabilities, and scale digital mobility architecture guided by Information
 Technology Infrastructure Library (ITIL) v4 methodologies and a centralized funding model. The DITI Developmental Cybersecurity effort also furnishes internal
 management of requirements, funding, contract actions, and PM support/training relating to the SSC S6.

 Lastly, DITI hosts the Cyber Halo Innovation Research Program (CHIRP). This program provides prospective students across various educational partners a two- year
 guided opportunity that leads them directly to critical cybersecurity careers that include infrastructure, the military sector, and various levels of government.




