                                $$, $$8027f94050f734b3ecb2cc0b9f374f9b8d0a37767f33635a07fe3038370e512e$$, $${"A": "6261f1641d0b95409ee902b258222f044c5e8d51e606238b0e8093dc483b0864", "C": "d4fdf923ba776b98bda680220afe7660b2fb7f78e25f4cb026ad0b29031d9620", "D": "2dc203d7bece77a7f653445bccb33a5587fda490b0326e34845bb537c0f52225"}$$::jsonb, $$Budget J-Books/FY26/Navy/RDTEN_BA5_Book.pdf$$, 749, $$2026-05-10T04:03:06.372628+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.pe_narratives (pe_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, accomplishments, planned_program, performance_metrics, other_program_funding, raw_text, content_hash, section_hashes, source_pdf, source_page, ingested_at) VALUES ($$0304784F$$, 2027, $$Long Endurance - Airborne Intelligence, Reconnaissance, and Surveillance

 The Long Endurance - Airborne Intelligence, Surveillance, and Reconnaissance (LE-AISR) program develops, matures, demonstrates, and assesses airborne platform
 capabilities that are able to operate for extended periods of time. The LE-AISR PE supports multiple types of long endurance programs intended to augment current
 airborne ISR capabilities and fill existing capability gaps. LE-AISR consists of three efforts: Uncrewed Long-endurance Tactical Reconnaissance Aircraft (ULTRA), High
 Altitude Long Endurance (HALE), and Emerging Capabilities. ULTRA is the only active effort in LE-AISR.

 Activities also include studies and analysis to support both current program planning and future program planning.

 This program element included all necessary expenses required to manage, execute, and deliver weapon system capability. The use of such program funds would be in
 addition to the civilian pay expenses budgeted in program elements 0605829F, 0605831F, 0605833F, and 0605898F

 In FY26, Uncrewed Long-endurance Tactical Reconnaissance Aircraft (ULTRA) transitioned to PE 0304784F - LE-AISR from PE 0305206F - Airborne Reconnaissance
 Systems (ARS). This program is not a new start as ULTRA has been executing from 0305206F, historically. In FY27, High Altitude Long Endurance (HALE) will also
 transition to PE 0304784F LE-AISR from PE 0305206F - ARS to separate sensors and sensor platforms. This program is not a new start.

 The FY 2026 spend plan amount for PE0304784F include $0 thousand of discretionary and $23,000 thousand of mandatory (reconciliation) for a total of $23,000
 thousand.

 Submitted an FY26 Internal Reprogramming (IR) for 20.170 million for ULTRA, an Internal Reprogramming (IR) will be processed aligning the funding to PE0304784F
 for proper execution.

 Airborne Reconnaissance Systems, received a Congressional add for FY2026 15.000 million for long endurance ISR. Upon Congressional spend plan approval, an
 Internal Reprogramming (IR) will be processed aligning the funding to PE0304784F for proper execution.

Operational Systems Development

 This program is in Budget Activity 7, Operational System Development because this budget activity includes development efforts to upgrade systems that have been
 fielded or have received approval for full rate production and anticipate production funding in the current or subsequent fiscal year.

 Program Title: ULTRA

 LE-AISR will develop the Uncrewed Long-endurance Tactical Reconnaissance Aircraft (ULTRA) prototype, demonstrate, and transition this emerging capability. The
 Uncrewed Long-endurance Tactical Reconnaissance Aircraft (ULTRA) prototype is developed to support airborne LE-AISR and demonstrate this technology in an
 Operational Assessment (OA). ULTRA is an Air Force-led technology and concept development effort to demonstrate an Unmanned Aerial System (UAS) that is capable
 of multiple-day duration flights while maintaining affordability. ULTRA leverages commercial-off-the-shelf (COTS) technologies to minimize expensive custom/proprietary
 items while at the same time simplifying maintenance and manpower costs. The payload integration for ULTRA maintains a modular and flexible architecture to allow
 for rapid integration of customer-driven payload options. ULTRA leverages and builds off the successes and lessons learned of several AFRL, DoD, and other partner
 funded development efforts, including the Long Endurance Aerial Platform (LEAP) UAS. The initial ULTRA UAS was developed in 2018 and flight-tested in 2019. In 2020
 ULTRA performed limited operational test and evaluation over a six-month period, the results of which informed payload and system requirements to meet current and
 future needs. ULTRA is an affordable ultra-long endurance ISR platform that is responsive to current and future needs. FY24 funding acquired 4 upgraded platforms.
 FY25 funding supports platform upgrades, integration, and training. FY26 funding will support an OCONUS OA in CENTCOM's Area of Responsibility (AOR), which
 is the next step (operational testing and evaluation) in developing the ULTRA system. This assessment will begin with the OCONUS OA in FY26. FY27 funding will
 continue the OA and fund needed capability improvements to meet user requirements. The ULTRA effort is not a new start. It is a flight demonstration of the ULTRA
 program, which includes an upgraded platform with Multi-INT capabilities. The ULTRA program was previously executed in FY 2024 under the Endurance Uncrewed
 Aerial Vehicles project and in FY 2025 under the Airborne Reconnaissance System.

 Program Title: HALE
 High Altitude Long Endurance (HALE) assets provide risk-reduction and alternative sensing capability employment options. This effort will initiate the pre-acquisition
 activity to develop a Family of Systems constellation to provide wide area intelligence, surveillance, and reconnaissance in highly contested environments.

 Program Title: Emerging Capabilities
 Emerging Capabilities advances the development, maturation, demonstration, and assessment of long endurance capabilities designed to address emerging and future
 challenges in dynamic operational environments.

 This program is in Budget Activity 7, Operational System Development because this budget activity includes development efforts to upgrade systems that have been
 fielded or have received approval for full rate production and anticipate production funding in the current or subsequent fiscal year.

