C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                   FY 2024     FY 2025      FY 2026
Title: Space Protection and Survivability                                                                                                63.784      53.199       45.200
Description: SSDP applies a holistic analytical approach to improve the resilience of NSS space effects for national security
missions.

FY 2025 Plans:
Fiscal Year 2025 will see continued organizational change, growth, and challenges within the United States Space Force (USSF)
and across the National Security Space (NSS) community. As an integral part of the community, the Space Security and Defense
Program (SSDP) will adapt to the inevitable changes and continue to provide our stakeholders with creative, informed, and
rigorously evaluated solutions for space superiority.

SSDP's analytical priorities for FY25 focus on the following: Ensuring Resilience of Near-term and Future Space and Space-
enabled Missions, Offensive Space Control (OSC) Force Design, Enhancing Space Control Weapon Effectiveness, and Space
and the Cross Domain Fight. As part of Ensuring Resilience of Near-term and Future Space and Space-enabled Missions,
SSDP will continue to focus on the resiliency of next-generation space missions and support to our stakeholders' development

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                   FY 2024    FY 2025      FY 2026
of Government Reference Architectures. Keeping pace with and getting ahead of adversary advances is a critical component of
our Offensive Space Control Force Design analysis. Specifying Space Force Design (offense and defense) is only the start of our
SSDP responsibilities. The program will also be focused on Enhancing Space Control Weapon Effectiveness; requiring SSDP
to collaborate with our stakeholders to ensure system readiness and effectivity. Finally, understanding the impact of space to
the cross-domain fight for both the US and our adversaries is an increasingly important aspect of SSDP's Space and the Cross-
Domain Fight responsibilities.

In the spirit of our charter, we will address these priorities through materiel and non-materiel solutions, kinetic and non-kinetic
options, cross-domain solutions, and policy, doctrine and strategic messaging analyses to support safe, sustainable, and flexible
on-orbit operations, and deter adversaries from engaging in space conflict.
FY 2026 Plans:
(U) Fiscal Year 2026 provides yet another year of continuous organizational change, growth, and challenges. As an integral part
of the National Security Space (NSS) community, SSDP adapts to the changing environment to provide our stakeholders relevant,
data-informed, and rigorously evaluated solutions for space superiority.
(U) SSDPS's four analytical priorities for FY26 focus on the following: Ensuring Resilience of Near-term and Future Space and
Space-enabled Missions; Space Control and Multi-Domain Force Designs; Space Control Force Development; and Space and
the Cross-Domain Fight. In support of the first analytic priority, SSDP will continue to focus on the resiliency of next-generation
space missions and support to our stakeholder's development of Government Reference Architectures. Keeping pace with and
getting ahead of adversary advances is a critical component of Space Control and Multi-Domain Force Design analysis and
recommendations. SSDP Space Control Force Development provides support to our partners while ensuring system readiness
and effectivity. Finally, understanding the impact of space to the cross-domain fight for both the US and our adversaries is an
increasingly important aspect of SSDP's Space and the Cross-Domain Fight responsibilities. Our integrated modeling and analysis
efforts continue to validate force design and joint service architecture recommendations (such as Assault Breaker II and other kill
chain analyses efforts).
(U) It is through such steadfast commitment that SSDP efforts will ensure opportunities for the U.S. to engage our adversaries
in any domain, at the time and location of our choosing, and in manners consistent with National Defense Strategy and National
Strategy for Space objectives.
FY 2025 to FY 2026 Increase/Decrease Statement:
FY 2025 to FY2026 funding decreased due to SSDP $8M reduction to fund Space Force Service priorities.
