        Change Summary Explanation
        The increase in FY 2024 from the Previous President's Budget to the Current President's Budget is due to a $38.000 million Congressional reduction of
        inadequate justification and a $252.785 million increase from the incorporation of funding previously programmed under Appropriation 3620, PE 1206448SF.

        The decrease in FY 2025 from the Previous President's Budget to the Current President's Budget is due to a $33.000 million Congressional reduction for
        Management Reserve reduction.

        The decrease in FY 2026 from the Previous President's Budget to the Current President's Budget is due to a decrease to align the SDA Tracking program to the
        Non-Advocate Cost Assessment (NACA) as well as an adjustment for other United States Space Force priorities.

        The FY 2026 request was reduced by $0.328 million for Advisory and Assistance Services to promote efficiencies and advance the policies of the Administration
        in alignment with Executive Order 14222, "Implementing the President's Department of Government Efficiency Cost Efficiency Initiative."

        The FY 2026 request for MW/MT/MD includes $1,757,354 thousand of discretionary and $823,000 thousand of mandatory (reconciliation) for a total of
        $2,580,354 thousand. The mandatory funds additional capabilities for space-based sensing for hypersonic fire control. Further information for this reconciliation
        request is provided in Section 20003 (Missile Defense) of the Reconciliation Exhibit.

        The increase in the Current President's Budget between the FY 2025 amount and the FY 2026 amount reflects the continued ramp up of Tranche 3 activities for
        space vehicle development, delivery, and test after the expected awards of Tranche 3 Tracking Layer Space Vehicle vendors in Quarter 4 FY 2025 / Quarter 1 FY
        2026.

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                               FY 2024      FY 2025      FY 2026
Title: Resilient Missile Warning Missile Tracking - Low Earth Orbit (LEO)                                                         1,481.222    1,697.821    1,757.354
Description: Rapidly develop, deploy and demonstrate prototype architecture that enables resilient Missile Warning/Missile
Tracking/Missile Defense (MW/MT/MD) enabled by a proliferated Low Earth Orbit (pLEO) architecture. This effort will define,
demonstrate, and deliver the architectures and standards necessary to fully populate a MW/MT/MD LEO layer as part of the
Proliferated Warfighter Space Architecture (PWSA).

FY 2025 Plans:
Tranche 1
- Conduct payload and space bus production and perform qualification testing.
- Integrate payloads and buses and conduct final space vehicle system Assembly, Integration and Testing (AI&T).
- Support Tracking Ground Readiness Review (GRR) to ensure integration with PWSA Operations Centers
- Complete initial integration with Missile Warning/Missile Tracking/Missile Defense (MW/MT/MD) enterprise data interfaces and
fusion applications.
- Perform Tracking payload ground calibration and complete space vehicle environmental test campaigns.
- Fund mission unique hardware and integration of the Tranche 1 (T1) space vehicles on the National Security Space Launch
(NSSL) Launch vehicles.
- Conduct Pre-Ship Review (PSR) for first Tracking plane launch.
- Support investments in facilities, hardware, network management, Ground Entry Points (GEPs), Optical Ground Terminals
(OGT), software development, mission payloads, contract services, and any other integration requirements to support the MW/
MT/MD enterprise. These efforts leverage and expand upon existing Mission Data Processing Applications (MDPAPs) and
Joint Overhead Persistent Infrared (OPIR) Ground initiatives to ensure rapid processing and dissemination to global warfighting
community.
- Support the planning and execution of performance and integration risk mitigation activities associated with command and
control (C2) challenges, MDP expansion, and interagency integration.
- Other activities may include program office support, studies, technical analysis, experimentation, prototyping, etc.

Tranche 2
- Complete Tranche 2 Tracking Layer (T2TRK) Preliminary Design Reviews (PDRs) and Critical Design Reviews (CDRs).
- Begin Optical Interoperability Testing (OIT) with T2TRK space vehicles to ensure optical connectivity.
- Begin payload proto-qual Assembly, Integration and Testing (AI&T).
- Begin spacecraft bus proto-qual AI&T.
- Initiate production of payloads and space buses.
- Support ground activities to ensure integration with Proliferated Warfighter Space Architecture (PWSA) Operations Centers.

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                              FY 2024      FY 2025      FY 2026
- Finalize initial phases of Technology Acceleration Center (TAC) development and ensure initial PWSA Ground Segment
integration for T2 launches and checkout activities.
- Continue Missile Warning/Missile Tracking/Missile Defense (MW/MT/MD) enterprise data integration with networks and fusion
applications.
- Begin space vehicle FlatSat development.
- Initiate Tracking space vehicle component deliveries and vehicle assembly and integration.
- Plan for Tracking payload ground calibration and begin space vehicle environmental test campaigns.
- Support investments in facilities, hardware, network management, Ground Entry Points (GEPs), Optical Ground Terminals
(OGT), software development, mission payloads, contract services, and any other integration requirements to support the MW/MT/
MD enterprise. These efforts leverage and expand upon existing Mission Data Processing Applications (MDPAPs) and Joint OPIR
Ground initiatives to ensure rapid processing and dissemination to global warfighting community.
- Support the planning and execution of performance and integration risk mitigation activities associated with command and
control (C2) challenges, MDP expansion, and interagency integration. Other activities include program office support, studies,
technical analysis, experimentation, prototyping, etc.
